$section Download and Install OMhelp$$
$index free, install$$ 
$index OMhelp, install$$
$index download, OMhelp$$


$head Notation$$
On Windows operating systems the directory separator is
the back slash $code \$$
and on Unix operating systems it is the forward slash $code /$$.
In some of the steps below the Unix and Windows cases
are given as one set of commands (and back slashes are used
for the directory separator). 
In these steps the back slashes should
be replaced by forward slashes 
for the Unix case.


$head Installation Directory$$
Choose the parent directory below which OMhelp will be installed;
for example, if you choose $code c:\$$, OMhelp will be installed 
in the $code c:\omhelp$$ directory.
All references to $italic parent$$ in this documentation
should be replaced by this parent directory.

$head Executing Commands$$
All the commands listed below are executed starting in the
$italic parent$$ directory.
In the Windows cases, you should use a Dos box to execute the commands.


$head Step 1: Environment Variable$$
$index environment, variable$$
$index variable, environment$$
$index omhelp_dir, environment variable$$
You must set the value of the environment variable 
$code omhelp_dir$$ to be equal to $syntax%parent%\omhelp%$$.
As mentioned above, 
$italic parent$$ is the parent directory for the installation.

$subhead Windows Source$$
You could execute the command
$syntax/
	set omhelp_dir=/parent/\omhelp
/$$
You could place this command in the file $code c:\autoexec.bat$$
so that it was executed each time a DOS box was opened.

$subhead Unix Source$$
You could execute the commands
$syntax%
	omhelp_dir=%parent%/omhelp
	export omhelp_dir
%$$
at the bash shell prompt.
You could place this command in the file $code ~/.profile$$
it will be executed each time a bash shell is started.


$head Step 2: Download Compressed OMhelp$$
Download the current Windows version of OMhelp by selecting 

$table
$bold Installation Type$$ $cnext
	$bold File Name$$ $rnext
Windows Source $cnext
	$href%
		http://www.seanet.com/~bradbell/OMhelp.dos.tar.gz%
		OMhelp.dos.tar.gz
	%$$ $rnext
Unix Source $cnext
	$href%
		http://www.seanet.com/~bradbell/OMhelp.unix.tar.gz%
		OMhelp.unix.tar.gz
	%$$
$tend

$subhead Windows Source$$
Use $href%http://www.winzip.com%WinZip%$$ (version 7.0 or higher),
or some other utility,
to decompress the files in 
$code OMhelp.dos.tar.gz$$.
Extract the resulting files into the
$italic parent$$ directory being sure to preserve
the structure of the sub-directories.
(all of the resulting files should be in the $code dos$$ subdirectory).
Then execute the following command
$codep
	rename dos omhelp
$$

$subhead Unix Source$$
Use the following commands to extract the OMhelp source code:
$codep
	gunzip OMhelp.unix.tar
	tar -xvf OMhelp.unix.tar
	mv unix omhelp
$$

$head Step 3: Build The Executable$$

$subhead Windows Source$$
You can either use $code nmake$$ or Microsoft Development Studio
to build the executable with Microsoft C/C++ compiler.
The following commands use $code nmake$$ to build the executable file
$syntax%%parent%\omhelp\omhelp.exe%$$:
$codep
	chdir omhelp\src
	nmake /f omhelp.mak
$$
The following steps use Microsoft Development Studio
to build the executable file 
$syntax%%parent%\omhelp\omhelp.exe%$$:
$list number$$
Open Microsoft Development Studio.
$lnext
Select $code File | Open | Project$$ an in the dialog that appears
select the file
$syntax%
	%parent%\omhelp\src\src.sln
%$$
and then select the $code Open$$ button.
$lnext
Select $code Build | Build src$$. 
$lend

$subhead Unix Source$$
The following command will build the executable file
$syntax%%parent%\omhelp\omhelp%$$:
$codep
	cd omhelp/src
	make
$$

$head Step 4: Generate Developer Documentation$$

$subhead Windows Source$$
$mindex developer documentation$$
The following commands will generate a local copy of the 
OMhelp developer documentation.
$codep
	cd omhelp\src\omh
	RunOMhelp
$$
This will execute the file $code RunOMhelp.bat$$
which uses OMhelp to create a copy of the 
OMhelp developer documentation in the directory
$syntax%%parent%\omhelp\src\omh\htm%$$.

$subhead Unix Source$$
The following commands will generate a local copy of the 
OMhelp developer documentation.
$codep
	cd omhelp/src/omh
	RunOMhelp
$$
This will execute the file $code RunOMhelp$$
which uses OMhelp to create a copy of the 
OMhelp developer documentation in the directory
$syntax%%parent%\omhelp\src\omh\htm%$$.

$head Step 5: Generate User Documentation$$
The following steps will generate a local copy of the OMhelp user 
documentation:

$subhead Windows Source$$
$codep
	cd omhelp\omh
	RunOMhelp
%$$
This will execute the file $code RunOMhelp.bat$$
which uses OMhelp to create a copy of the 
OMhelp user documentation in the directory
$syntax%%parent%\omhelp\omh\htm%$$.

$subhead Unix Source$$
$codep
